'''Michael "Mike" Hayes''' is an English businessman, best known as the president and CEO of SEGA Europe and SEGA of America (collectively [[SEGA|SEGA West]]). He has also held executive positions at Codemasters and Nintendo UK and currently leads the digital and e-commerce division of [[Mercia Fund Management]].<ref name="Weber">{{Cite news |url=http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2013-09-19-ex-sega-ceo-joins-vc-fund-mercia-fund-management |title=Ex-Sega CEO joins VC fund Mercia Fund Management |last=Weber |first=Rachel |date=19 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/200488/Former_Sega_CEO_Mike_Hayes_heading_up_new_game_VC_fund.php |title=Former Sega CEO Mike Hayes heading up new game VC fund |date=18 September 2013 |first=Mike |last=Rose}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.develop-online.net/news/mike-hayes-heads-vc-s-new-games-division/0115874 |title=Mike Hayes heads VC's new games division |first=Seth |last=Tipps |date=19 September 2013}}</ref>

==Career==

Mike Hayes' earliest video game credits show that he was involved in the localization of [[Starcraft]] at [[Blizzard Entertainments]] in 1998.<ref name="Moby">{{Cite web |url=http://www.mobygames.com/developer/sheet/view/by_title/developerId,374071/|title=Mike Hayes |accessdate=6 October 2013}}</ref>From 2002 to 2003 he is credited in various [[Codemasters]] games for a role in public relations.<ref name="Moby"/>

During the late 1980s Mike was employed by General Foods (soon to be bought by Kraft), where he was a Brand Manager and then Marketing Manager on their desserts products including Angel Delight and Bird's Custard. It is unknown where he was employed between then and 2001.

He joined the company in 2004 as Managing Director.<ref>[[Head Hunter: Redemption]] Manuals</ref> In 2005, Hayes became president contributing to the company's reinvention from a hardware maker to a third-party games publisher. In his tenure as COO of SEGA Europe, he was credited for restoring SEGA's dominance in Europe by setting up the now-defunct [[Sega Racing Studio]] and acquiring video game studios [[Creative Assembly]] and [[Sports Interactive]].<ref name="Maxwell">{{Cite news |url=http://www.edge-online.com/news/sega-europe-and-us-boss-mike-hayes-step-down/ |title=Sega Europe and US boss Mike Hayes to step down |first=Ben |last=Maxwell |date=30 April 2012}}</ref> 

In June 2009, Mike Hayes replaced [[Simon Jeffery]] as President of Sega of America, becoming the head of all Western SEGA branches.<ref>[http://www.seganerds.com/2009/06/16/mike-hayes-promoted-to-president-of-sega-west/ Seganerds.com]</ref><ref>[http://www.mcvuk.com/news/34736/Hayes-set-for-global-Sega-rolern MCVUK.com]</ref> He remained Sega's president until June 2012.<ref name="Weber"/>

